answers.body_markdown:
The mapping you have for `AProductPhone` doesn&#39;t use hibernate inheritance and that causes the problem. You need use the `@Inheritance` annotation using the table-per-subclass strategy (assuming you want a different table per subclass). This will create one table for the superclass and one table per subclass.

As an example (imagine an abstract bank account with 2 subtypes):
```
@Entity
@Inheritance(
      strategy= InheritanceType.TABLE_PER_CLASS
)
@DiscriminatorColumn(name=&quot;TYPE&quot;)
public abstract class Account {
   @Id
   private Long id;

   private double balance;

   [...]
}

@Entity
@DiscriminatorValue(&quot;CHECKING&quot;)
public class CheckingAccount extends Account {
   private double checkLimitAmount;
   [...]
}

@Entity
@DiscriminatorValue(&quot;SAVINGS&quot;)
public class SavingsAccount extends Account  {
   private double atmLimit;
   [...]
}
```

With the configuration above, one can have a `@OneToMany List&lt;Account&gt;` mapped from other entities.

